>She first asked me if I was hungry, I said yes, then asked me if I was tired, and I also said yes. Instead of grabbing my hand or guiding me off the sofa, she simply lifted me off the couch. I immediately found myself gingerly being carried through the house, like a helpless idiot. I didn't look at her face while I was in this state, but I did notice her tail wagging breezily. It only added to the fact that I was more offended than uncomfortable. She strode through the hall like she walked on air, and I was gently presented to the bed as she tore away the blankets. The vast and cozing stillness enveloped my body as she pulled the blanket back over me, and stepped back, kneeling to ask me one question. Her dark eyes, pointed by that unexpressive light, were glassy and shallow. "Need anything else?"
>I caught it this time. The light blinked off, for half a second, "I need to use the bathroom."
>So then, she brushed the covers aside and led me to the bathroom. Once I was done, she was standing right outside the door, looming over me politely just as she had for the past three days. She greeted me with a smile and a tail wag in an almost disgustingly predictable manner, then we retraced our steps all the way back to bed. This time, she made sure to pat the blankets down over me. She squatted next to me again, unexpressive expression expressing only a soft smile and relaxed gaze, but no intent beyond a spoken question, "Are you okay?"
>I bury my nose under the blanket and do my best to nod, even though my alotness seemed to steal the words from my mouth.
She stands up and goes to touch my head, but I shrink and cover it by accident. Luckily, she doesn't mind and just says, "Dinner will be ready shortly." and walks out of the room, giving me one last smile and a small bow before flicking the light off and gently clicking the door behind her.
